The paper deals with privacy-type properties of security protocols, which are typically modelled using process algebras. The focus is on deciding trace equivalence properties for finite processes, which suggests a logical and formal methods approach. This makes cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) the most likely category. However, the paper also mentions symbolic execution and constraint solving, which are techniques used in program analysis and verification, suggesting cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) and cs.PL (Programming Languages) as possible categories. The paper also discusses partial order reduction techniques, which are used to reduce the number of interleavings explored during verification, suggesting cs.SE (Software Engineering) as another possible category. Finally, the paper deals with equivalence checking, which is a topic in formal methods and verification, suggesting cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) as a possible category.
